 Building African Scientific Ability (to hold or do something) for 
 Farming-based Development 
 Carl K. Eicher 
 Department of Farming-based Money flow, Michigan State University, East Lansing, 
 Ml 48824-1039 (U.S.A.) 
 (Accepted 16 May 1989) 
 
 Abstract 
 Eicher, C.K., 1990. Building African scientific ability (to hold or do something) for farming-based development. Agric. Econ., 
 4: 117-143. 
 During Africa's first twenty years of independence from 1960 to 1980, priority was given to increasing the size of national extension services because it was assumed that technology could be 
 imported from industrial countries and the International Farming-based Research Centers. Over the 
 past ten years, (people who give money or other things) have turned their attention to helping national farming-based research 
 systems (NARS). But many NARS are (doing/completing) poorly and are faced with a high turnover of 
 scientific staff and (not good enough) operating budgets. More than that, the present donor-financed project by 
 project and country by country approach to building African scientific ability (to hold or do something) is seriously flawed. 
 This paper examines Africa's farming-based research history over the past sixty years and draws 
 lessons for strengthening national and (related to a large area) farming-based research systems over the coming 30 
 years. 
 
 "The true measure of the success of a program of international and technical cooperation is not in its completed things during the period it is in force but rather in 
 what happens after money from other countries has been withdrawn." 
 -George HARRAR, 1967, p. 20. 
 
 Introduction 
 The biggest challenge facing the international farming-based research community in the 1990s is sub-Saharan Africa, a continent of 45 (many different kinds of people or things) (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 and 500 million people. The development of improved technology through 
 farming-based research is central in facing Africa's dual problems of lazy food production and (away from cities) poorness. From independence in 1960-1980, 
 (people who give money or other things) helped in expanding national extension services in Africa because it 
 was assumed that improved technology could be borrowed from industrial 
 countries and international farming-based research centers. Starting around 
 
 0169-5150/90/$03.50 
 
