 118 
 
 1980, (people who give money or other things) offered (for only a short time) project support to strengthen national 
 farming-based research systems (NARS) in Africa. But Africa has one-fifth the 
 number of R&amp;D scientists and engineers per million people as Asia. More than that, 
 about one-fourth of the total number of farming-based (people who work to find information) in NARS and 
 school-related staff in Teachers/professors of Farming in Africa are (ban from a country). In short, 
 after thirty years of independence, Africa has a low level of scientific ability (to hold or do something). 
 This paper presents some thoughts on building African scientific ability (to hold or do something) 
 and strengthening national and (related to a large area) farming-based research systems 
 (NARS) in sub-Saharan Africa (Africa) over the next 30 years. The big idea of 
 this paper is that since many African countries are generations behind Asian 
 and Latin American countries in terms of their stage of scientific ability 
 and institutional maturity, the (for only a short time) project approach now used by 
 (people who give money or other things) to build African scientific ability (to hold or do something) should be replaced by long-term 
 institution-building approaches that were effective in Asia in the 1960s and 
 1970s. But because of Africa's cultural and institutional (many different kinds of people or things), no single 
 model of institution-building should be forced on Africa. More than that, because 
 of the differential stage of development among African countries, institutionbuilding approaches that are effective in middle-income countries such as Zimbabwe and the Cameroon, will have to be changed for countries at an earlier 
 stage of development, such as Guinea, Chad, Burundi, Somalia and Uganda. 
 The performance and (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) of NARS will be examined over two 30year periods: the colonial period from 1930 to 1959 and after-independence from 
 1960 to 1989. This historical test raises some longer-term issues to 
 think about in strengthening NARS over the coming 30 years, 1990-2020. Finally, 
 some of the effects/results/suggestions are explored for African states, and (people who give money or other things). 
 
 African development big picture 
 In 1957, Ghana, earlier the Gold Coast, reached its independence in the middle of  an 
 outpouring of joy and high expectations. Three years later, 17 added/more countries won their independence, this way explaining why 1960 is often referred to as 
 the date of Africa's independence. Today, 45 countries totaling around 500 
 million people make up sub-Saharan Africa. But (even though there is the existence of) the joy going along with independence in the late 1950s and early 1960s, there has been a basic (existence of two things that aren't equal in size, power, color, etc.) between the huge physical production (possible power or ability within/possibility of) 
 Africa and the ability (to hold or do something) of African governments to reach their money-based 
 wishes. Africa's poorness is (taken by force/controlled) in a single statistic: the total GNP of 
 the 45 countries in sub-Saharan Africa in 1985 was (a) little less than the total 
 GNP of Spain, a nation of 40 million (World Bank, 1987a). 
 African states are usually small in terms of population. Half of the 45 
 countries have fewer than 5 million people, pointing up the need to examine 
 
 119 
 
 how NARS in these countries can chase after what Emil JAVIER calls "smart 
 borrowing" as the first (or most important) plan for owning new technology. Smart 
 and planned borrowing of technology is the common symbol of the energetic 
 money-based growth of Japan, Singapore, South Korea and other countries, including The Netherlands, where now about half of the technology used 
 by farmers is imported. Anyway, there is a view in some scientific circles 
 in Africa that borrowing is an inferior (related to computers and science) path. 
 The stage of institutional development of African states relative to Asia and 
 Latin America is a sensitive topic that was avoided in the early years of 
 Africa's independence in the 1960s and 1970s and is slowly starting to be 
 discussed openly. For example, the respected Africanist, Colin Legum, (not very long ago) watched/followed that as colonial powers withdrew from the continent in 1960, they 
 "left behind them a series of national states, but very few nation-states. The 
 level of development of the continent's nation-state was still roughly 
 equal to that of Europe or China in the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries 
 - and certainly no later than the seventeenth century" (Legum, 1985, p. 24). 
 The early stage of Africa's development is limiting the amount offoreign aid 
 that can be now soaked up with good quality/completeness. Most (people who give money or other things) are ignoring the 
 different stage of institutional maturity of individual Mrican states as they 
 prepare standard 5-7-year projects to strengthen NARS and national extension services. More than that, these (for only a short time) projects are always 'front-loaded' 
 with quick-paying activities such as buildings, vehicles, and equipment. 
 A few studies are starting to document the scientific and institutional gap 
 between Africa, and Latin America and Asia (Lele and Goldsmith, 1989). For 
 example, Shapiro (1985) has shown that Africa has about one-fourth the 
 number of scientists, engineers and managers per million people as Asia. Twothirds of the villages in India were excited/with electricity in 1987 as compared with a small 
 fraction in most African countries. Sri Skinnya and Sierra Leone both had percapita incomes of $330 in 1983, but the (how long a person is expected to live) was 69 years in Sri 
 Skinnya as compared with 38 years in Sierra Leone (Behrman et al., 1988). 
 There are written records of farmer crop-watering/rinsing with water associations in Thailand dating 
 back 600 years (Surareks, 1986). Very differently, farmer crop-watering/rinsing with water associations 
 are in their (very beginning stages) in Africa because only 3-5% of the cropped land is under 
 (producing crops/helping something grow) as compared with 30-50% in Asia. A recent study of 25 World 
 Bank-financed farming-based development projects in East Asia, Latin America 
 and Africa points to big differences in the (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) of 
 farming-based projects by continent. The study shows/tells about that all of the ten projects 
 in Latin America and Asia were thought about/believed (money-based)/cheaply (able to last/helping the planet), compared with only two of the 15 projects in Africa (Cernea, 1987, p. 4). These studies suggest that donor-financed farming-based projects, including support to 
 NARS in Africa, should be designed differently than those in Asia and Latin 
 America. But, Africa's scientific and institutional gap should be expected 
 
 120 
 
 because it is partially the unstoppable result of a century of colonial 
 underinvestment in developing Africa's scientific and managerial ability (to hold or do something). 
 Also, it should be kept in mind that most African countries have been independent for barely 30 years relative to 150 years in Latin America. 
 
 Institutions, (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) and African development 
 In this paper, I have used a broad definition of institutions to include institutions and organizations and the rules and conventions that govern them. Over 
 the past twenty years, there has been a lack of hard (related to careful studying or deep thinking) and scientific 
 research on the money flow/money-based studies, financing and (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) of (related to a plan to reach a goal) national 
 farming-based institutions, such as NARS and extension services. For example, 
 to date there is not a single published study of the money flow/money-based studies of investment in 
 farming-based research for any NARS in sub-Saharan Africa. As a result, 
 (ability to be done) teams are forced to use rate of return guesses from studies in Asia 
 and Latin America to permit donor investments in valuable thing research, FSR 
 projects &#126;nd NARS in Mrica. But this should not come as a surprise. The late 
 Gunnar Myrdal reports that when he was carrying out research for Asian 
 Drama in the 1960s, the hardest issue was learning how "to deal with 
 the political issues of changing institutions, which were then, as now, avoided 
 by most ordinary money-flow experts in their writings on development" (Myrdal, 1984, 
 p. 154). 
 Anyway, the study of institutions is growing in (quality of being liked a lot or done a lot) among 
 money-flow experts. In a 20-year (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something) of the money-based development process in 
 23 countries over the 1850-1914 period, two smart people  (not very long ago) decided that 
 "institutions mattered most in telling the difference between country groups experiencing more successful and less successful money-based development" (Morris 
 and Adelman, 1988, p. 209). The authors decided that "(many different kinds of people or things) in growth, 
 (many different kinds of people or things) in institutions and (many different kinds of people or things) in related explanations were the 
 common symbols of the process of nineteenth century development." Glenn L. 
 Johnson argues that "institutional limits are now the most 
 serious holding back factor" on farming in the developed, newly improved and developing countries (Johnson, 1989, p. 177). 
 (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) came of age with the (book, magazine, etc.) of Our Common Future, commonly known as the Brundtland report (World Commission on (surrounding conditions) 
 and Development, 1987). But to date, there has been little debate on the (things that decide other things) of (able to last/helping the planet) farming-based institutions in Mrica. A (able to last/helping the planet) 
 NARS must meet three basic needed things. First, a (able to last/helping the planet) NARS must 
 be able to meet a performance test: the ability to plan and put into use national 
 research programs and develop improved technology in an (producing a lot with very little waste) manner. 
 Second, a (able to last/helping the planet) NARS must have the ability to change and change  in 
 order to meet the changing research needs of its clients and important people over 
 
 121 
 
 time. Third, a (able to last/helping the planet) NARS must (put into a hospital)/(make a behavior acceptable) the ability to 
 create domestic money-based help and develop a stable group of national 
 scientists to carry out its research mission in line with changing (things that are important). 
 The hard core knowledge base on how to strengthen institutions such as 
 NARS, extension services and faculties of farming in Africa is sadly not enough. Research is very much needed on the causes of the (existing all over a large area) failure 
 of parastatals and the poor performance of national research and extension 
 services (Eicher, 1982; Lipton, 1988). But research should also examine why 
 some farming-based institutions are extremely effective such as the Kenya Tea 
 Development Authority that serves 150 000 smallholders, the Zimbabwe 
 Smallholder Cotton Marketing Board, the Botswana Meat Commission, West 
 Cameroon Coffee Cooperative Union, and the Mali Sud Cotton Project that 
 serves 70 000 smallholders. These success stories should be carefully studied 
 to draw lessons for institution building in the 1990s. 
 Thirty years of independence have produced a large knowledge base on 
 why many money from other countries-financed farming-based and (away from cities) development projects 
 are not (doing as expected) well at this early stage of Africa's money-based history and institutional easily-broken quality (Cernea, 1987; World Bank, 1987b, 1988d; Eicher, 1989). 
 There is consistent (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that human ability and institutional (blocking things) 
 to development have been skirted in the drive to increase money from other countries flows to 
 African farming - especially during the fast build-up of aid for direct action projects over the 1973-83 period. Starting around 1983, the money from other countries 
 pendulum swung from project to policy-based lending. But (without any concern about/having nothing to do with) 
 whether the focus was on project or policies, the result has been the same: 
 the long-run human ability, scientific and institutional and social organizational issues - the most important movers of farming-based development - are being 
 seriously neglected by both African policy makers and (people who give money or other things). There is a need 
 for a basic reexamination of the ideas (you think are true) about Africa's stage of 
 money-based history, the differential levels of development of different African 
 states, (able to/ability to hold or take in something else) ability (to hold or do something), repeating costs and plans for building African 
 ability (to hold or do something) in research, extension, and training. 
 The longer one works in Africa, the more one is forced to decide that a 
 human ability/institution building model of development should replace 
 the long term technical help and across-the-ocean training model. The faults/problems of the technical help model are painfully seen/obvious in Somalia. A recent joint UNDP/IBRD technical mission dug deeply into the mode of delivering money from other countries to Somalia, a country ripped apart with group  wars and a century or 
 two behind most Asian countries in terms of its level of scientific, institutional, 
 and (related to managing and running a company or organization) maturity. The mission reported that (people who give money or other things) were together pumping US$100 million into Somalia each year to support 1200 (ban from a country)s on technical help contracts to different government (services businesses/government units) 
 
 122 
 
 and ove\seas training for Somali nationals (UNDP and IBRD, 1985).1 Anyway, this revolving door model of foreign advisors and across-the-ocean training is 
 not (accomplishing or gaining) the final/best goal, "the development of national ability (to hold or do something) 
 through the permanent move (from one place to another) of skills and know-how to Somali nationals 
 and national institutions" (UNDP and IBRD, 1985, p. 2). Without question, 
 the model is not facing the long-term problem of developing (able to last/helping the planet) 
 Somali institutions. 
 We will  now examine Africa's colonial farming-based research history from 
 1930 to the eve of independence in 1959. 
 
 Farming-based research during the colonial period: 1930- 1959 
 National farming-based research services 
 
 A extremely skinny/skeleton-related farming-based research (set of machines) was established in most 
 countries in Africa during the first two to thirty years of this century. 2 A 
 few countries such as the Sudan launched research programs immediately 
 following World War I (Idris, 1969). By 1930, small groups of (people who work to find information) were 
 at work on export valuable things, but food crop research included (grass grown for food) in 
 Uganda, maize in Zimbabwe and Kenya, rice and cassava in Zaire, and rice 
 in English speaker and francophone West Africa. In most countries, a few scientists 
 worked on clearly stated/particular crops in a loose organization which was more modest than 
 present-day national farming-based research systems. The exception was the 
 huge Belgian research operation in Zaire (earlier the Belgian Congo). 
 The (ability to create interesting new things) and working well of NARS during the colonial period can be 
 illustrated through historical sketches of research in Zaire, Zimbabwe and 
 Kenya over the 1930-59 period. In Zaire, about two-thirds of the budget ofthe 
 Belgian-financed national farming-based research service (INEAC) was focused 
 on export crops and one-third on food crops. 3 Research on oil palm was launched in 1933 with the goal of developing a high-cooperating with/producing/giving up palm to replace the tall, 
 (producing or giving very little)ing wild palm that grew in the bush in West and Central Africa. In 
 1939, after only 6 years of research at the INEAC station at Yangambi in northern Zaire, a team of five colonial (people who work to find information) unlocked the (the study of tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) of the oil 
 palm that led to the development of blended varieties that out-cooperated with/produced/gave up wild 
 
