 Coast), 4 Nigeria (Eicher, 1967), Malaysia (Hartley, 1970), and Indonesia. 
 Research "spillovers" refer to the benefits from research which build up to 
 farmers and people in countries that import technology without paying for 
 the cost of its development. 
 INEAC's rice research also (shows or proves) the (related to a large area) spillover effects of a 
 technology-producing national farming-based research system (TP/NARS). In 
 1958, INEAC released an upland rice variety, O.S.6, after 6 years of breeding. 
 Although O.S.6 is not grown in Zaire, it remains one of the most in control/most common upland 
 rice varieties in West Africa 30 years after its release. O.S.6. is grown under 
 different local names in West Africa and it accounts for about 90% of the 
 upland rice now grown in Nigeria. In summary, the INEAC research program in Zaire illustrates the huge (possible power or ability within/possibility of)  national research services in 
 Africa to produce new food and export crop technology for local needs as well 
 as the needs of surrounding technology borrowing (TB) NARS. 
 The NARS of Zimbabwe is the second example of the (ability to create interesting new things) of a national 
 research system in Africa. Combination maize development in Zimbabwe from 1932 
 to 1960 represents an example of a NARS in Africa producing new 
 technology without depending on imported germplasm. In 1932, H.C. Arnold 
 launched a maize improvement program in Zimbabwe (then Southern 
 Rhodesia) followed by A.G.R. Rattray in 1938. In 1949, 17 years after research 
 was started, the first combination, SR-1, was developed by crossing two locally raised/trained 
 open-(brought pollen from one plant to another) varieties, Southern Cross and Salisbury White. But SR-1 was 
 not released to farmers because yields were low and research continued from 
 1949 to 1960 in a search for higher-cooperating with/producing/giving up combinations. In 1960, SR-52 (Southern 
 Rhodesia-52), a single-cross combination, was released to commercial farmers after 
 28 years of research on combinations (1932-1960). Looking back over the past six 
 20 years of research on food crops in Africa, the SR-52 white maize combination is 
 definitely the Green Revolution food crop success story in Africa (Eicher, 
 1984). Although the size of the maize research program in Zimbabwe has been 
 small (two to four (people who work to find information)), the program is known for its (unbroken, constant quality), its 
 scientific and (related to managing and running a company or organization) leadership and its working well. 5 Zimbabwe's exIn 1947, the French established the Institut de interesting pour les huiles et 
 oleangineaux (IRHO) to carry out research on oil palm. Cooperation between INEAC 
 and IRHO scientists played a very important role in developing the modern oil palm industry 
 in Cote d'Ivoire (Drachoussoff, 1965). 
