 (related to a large area) research institutes 
 
 (related to a large area) research institutions were introduced during the colonial period to 
 deal with the small country problem and stimulate the production of export 
 valuable things for (related to Europe) markets (Kyomo, 1988). In 1930, Ghana was the 
 world's largest cocoa producer, but the industry was harmed by insect and 
 disease problems. To deal with these problems, in 1938 the British colonial service established a Cocoa Research Institute at Tafo to serve Ghana. The Institute carried out highly successful studies of controlling a few cocoa 
 sicknesses, including swollen shoot virus, capsid and black pod. Spraying programs based on these research findings were useful in boosting 
 Ghana's cocoa production to a peak output of 520 000 metric tonnes in 1965 
 (Martinson et al., 1987). 
 In 1944, the Cocoa Research Institute of Ghana was renamed the West 
 African Cocoa Research Institute (W ACRI) and given a order to serve the 
 British (groups of people or other living things) of Ghana and Nigeria. The WACRI staff in 1944 was composed 
 of 15 British scientists. W ACRI had a productive life span of 18 years but in 
 1962, 5 years after independence, the government of Ghana ended/stopped W ACRI 
 and set up the Cocoa Research Institute of Ghana (CRIG). In the move/change from a 
 (related to a large area) to a national order, twelve (ban from a country) staff quit, leaving seven 
 local professional staff and 25 vacancies at (CRIG). The number of Ghanaian 
 scientific staff increased slowly to eleven (of 17 total) in 1970 and to 25 by 1985. 
 The order of CRIG was expanded in 1975 to include coffee, kola, and shea 
 nuts. 
 But the Cocoa Research Institute of Chana (CRIG) has been shoved by 
 changing government decisions on its (related to managing and running a company or organization) home. For example, 
 CRIG has been given by the following six organizations from 1962 to 
 1989: 
 National Research Group of people 
 Ghana College/school of Sciences, 
 Group of people for Scientific and Industrial Research (CSIR) 
 
 125 
 
 - Ministry of Cocoa Affairs 
 - Ghana Cocoa Marketing Board, and 
 - Ghana Cocoa Board. 
 CGIG has been reshuffied on the average of once every 4.5 years. No scientific 
 organization can wave/grow/decoration in an (surrounding conditions) of such organizational confusion. 
 We now turn to oil palm research in West Africa. Nigeria was the world's 
 leading producer of oil palm during the colonial period and in 1939, the British 
 colonial government established the Nigerian Oil Palm Research Station in 
 Benin in order to meet the growing challenge of oil palm production on (large farms with crops) in the Far East. In 1951, the British converted Nigeria's oil palm station 
 into the West African Institute for Oil Palm Research (WAIFOR), with a order to serve the British West African (land areas owned or controlled by someone) of Nigeria, Ghana, Sierra 
 Leone and the Cameroon. In the 1950s, WAIFOR was a highly productive 
 (related to a large area) research organization with a scientific staff of 16 senior officers 
 (WAIFOR, 1955-56). 
 Soon after Nigeria became independent in 1960, the new government decided to (convert to government ownership/make nation-wide) WAIFOR and rename it the Nigerian Institute for Oil Palm 
 Research (NIFOR). During the 1962-64 change period, ten of the 15 
 research officers left the Institute. When NIFOR was formally established in 
 1964, it had a staff of ten senior officers and the number increased slowly to 
 15 in 1970. Nigeria's oil boom of the 1970s gave/given money available for a (atomic) 
 jump in NIFOR's staff from 15 senior officers in 1970-71 to 283 in 1985 
 (NIFOR, 1965-66, 1970-71, 1985). 
 But today, NIFOR is not (doing as expected) well. Most of NIFOR's budget is used 
 to pay the (moneys paid for working) of its huge (related to managing and running a company or organization), scientific and support staff. Only 
 about 1/3 of its 283 senior staff are directly working at research while the other 
 2/3 are in management, support services, social services and money/money income 
 creating activities. NIFOR's research order has been broadened beyond 
 oil palm to include date palm, raphia, coconut and other palms. But in 1985, 
 only 48 scientists were working on the key crop - oil palm - while 64 out of 
 the 283 senior officers were (controlling or managing/giving medicine or something else) the Institute. NIFOR is also starved 
 for foreign exchange to buy equipment and supplies. In summary, NIFOR 
 is top heavy with (related to managing and running a company or organization) staff and it has a order looking like a 
 government development corporation. Many specialists believe that oil palm 
 research in Nigeria is less productive today with 283 senior officers than when 
 it had 15 from 1955 to 1970. 
 The spoiling of cocoa and oil palm research in Ghana and Nigeria stands 
 very different than the experience of Malaysia and Indonesia. In 1925, 
 Malaysia established the Rubber Research Institute of Malaysia (RRIM) and 
 concentrated its national research effort on rubber for forty years. Malaysia 
 became independent in 1957, the same year as Ghana, but Malaysia chose the 
 farming-based road to development while, under Nkrumah, Ghana chose the 
 
 126 
 
 industrial path. In the late 1960s, Malaysia began a huge 
 farming-based (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) program away from rubber by beginning and building on the 
 Malaysian Farming-based Research and Development Institute (MARDI) in 
 1971. Malaysia drew on Zaire's new research on combination palms (Beirnaert, 1940) and over time developed combinations good for Malaysian conditions. In 1978, oil palm research was spun off from MARDI into a new institute, the Palm Oil Research Institute of Malaysia (PORIM, 1985). Malaysia 
 is also planning to spin off cocoa research from MARDI and set up a separate 
 cocoa research institute with the goal of around 100 scientists and technicians. 
 Malaysia increased its farming-based research staff from 100 officers at independence in 1957 to 1000 today. Malaysia's highly productive research 
 system has helped (branch out into different things) its export base, and Malaysia is now regularly selling palm oil to Nigeria. Ghana's per person GDP of $390 in 1986 stands in 
 sharp contrast to $1830 in Malaysia. 
 Nigeria and Ghana have disappeared/wasted their research base for oil palm and 
 cocoa and lost world (your share of sales out of all sales)s to Malaysia and Indonesia. Restoring the 
 competitive position of oil palm and cocoa research will require more than increased (money-related) help from (people who give money or other things). Many basic political, managerial and 
 scientific problems are annoying/harming export crop research in West Africa. These 
 problems must be talked to/looked at by Africans at both the political and scientific 
 levels. 
 But in francophone Africa a few (related to a large area) research programs are still (doing as expected) well. One of the most successful is the CFDT/ffiCT network that supports cotton production and marketing in ten countries in francophone 
