 Five lessons from the colonial research experience 
 Colonial research included many failures such as the inability to (accomplish or gain with effort) 
 breakthroughs in (grass grown for food) and millet after sixty years of research, 
 underinvestment in training African scientists and the pursuit of inappropriate research plans in many land plentiful countries (Carr, 1982; 
 Binswanger, 1986). But (even though there is the existence of) these faults/problems, there were some stunning 
 successes in organizing, financing and executing colonial research that have 
 relevance for modern farming-based research policy in Africa: 
 
 1. Small valuable thing research teams. In most cases, three to four scientists, 
 and in a few cases, no more than half twelve scientists, formed the valuable thing 
 teams ofTP/NARS that produced combination maize in Zimbabwe and Kenya, rustresistant wheat in Kenya, improved tea copies in East Africa, cotton in U ganda, and improved soybean and cotton varieties in Zimbabwe. 
 2. (ability to create interesting new things) of technology producing NARS (TPINARS). During the colonial 
 period, many countries (showed/shown or proved) the (ability to create interesting new things) of national 
 farming-based research systems in producing new technology. 8 
 3. Borrowing technology. Borrowing technology is a proven colonial research 
 plan. The tea industry in Eastern Africa drew heavily on imported copies 
 from Sri Skinnya and India. Zimbabwe's SR52 maize seed was borrowed by a 
 dozen African countries. 
 4. Research spillovers: (related to a large area), Pan African, and international. Research 
 spillovers from TP/NARS and (related to a large area) starts are illustrated by combination oil 
 palm, combination maize, cotton and other valuable things. For example, Cote d'Ivoire, 
 Nigeria, Malaysia, and Indonesia borrowed the basic breeding plan for 
 combination oil palm from Zaire and used it to develop combinations for local conditions. 
 The spillover issue should be clearly incorporated in (investigations to see if something can be done) to 
 strengthen NARS in the 1990s. 9 
 5. (related to a large area) research: (producing a lot with very little waste) but dependent upon external financing. (related to a large area) research was chased after to serve the large number of small (groups of people or other living things). It was highly (producing a lot with very little waste) because of its concentration on a few valuable things, 
