 Farming-based research since independence: 1960- 1989 
 The total experience ofNARS in the first thirty years of independence 
 can be carefully studied under five topics: 
 
 Political confusion, destruction of institutions, and the brain drain. At independence, the institutional base of African farming was geared to 
 supporting large farms, (large farms with crops), ranches and export farming. The 
 1960s and 1970s were marked by the destruction of many of the born-in 
 (related to a large area) and national research institutions. Soon after independence, for example, Guinea and Madagascar ended/fired the services of French research 
 help. 'ln 1962, Nkrumah stopped Ghana's national extension service. 
 Tanzania stopped local government and farm cooperatives in the mid-1970s. 
 Many training institutions, such as Makerere University in Uganda, 
 were ruined during internal political big changes. 
 The localization and basic rebuilding of land-related institutions to serve the 
 majority of (away from cities) people is now happening throughout Africa. English speaker 
 countries such as Nigeria, Kenya, Ghana, and Tanzania have (accomplished or gained) 
 (in a big way) greater progress in the (conversion to government ownership/making something nation-wide) of their NARS and 
 Faculties of Farming than francophone countries. For example, after 29 
 years of independence, Cote d'Ivoire has 73% of its farming-based research and 
 teaching posts filled by (ban from a country)s as compared with 6% in Ghana and none 
 in Nigeria (Pardey and Roseboom, 1989). This is a puzzle that warrants further 
 analysis and debate at the political and technical levels. 
 Without question, one of the underreported events limiting African 
 farm-related today is the farming-based brain drain that has been fueled by plans, 
 (wars between groups that all live in one country) and political unrest. For example, Ghana, Ethiopia, Uganda, 
 Somalia, Tanzania, and Zambia have been stripped of farming-based scientists 
 and teachers through the brain drain. 
 Uncontrolled growth ofthe state slow-working department. Thirty years of independence have 
 been marked by an increase in the state machinery serving farming: 
 Sub-Saharan Africa started independence in 1960 with a deep/extreme extension bias of 21 200 extension agents and 1329 (people who work to find information). This bias was stronger as African states hired an added 36 000 extension agents over 
 the next 20 years (Judd et al., 1987, pp. 11-13). 
 
 129 
 
 - The Congo increased the size of its extension staff ten-fold from 1960 to 
 1972 (Young, 1988, p. 26). 
 - In Ghana, the Cocoa Marketing Board employed 105 000 in the early 1980s 
 to handle a crop half as large as that which 50 000 workers had managed 
 in 1965 (Young, 1988). 
 In Nigeria, the national farming-based research service expanded from 100 
 (people who work to find information) in 1960 to around 1000 today (Pardey and Roseboom, 1989). 
 In many cases, the (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of the state institutions has been went with 
 by an wearing away in the performance of the institutions, with most of the 
 budget used to pay (moneys paid for working) (Abernethy, 1987). 
 
 The Green Revolution footprint. The Green Revolution has (accomplished or gained) the hit/effect of a small footprint on Africa's (away from cities) (wide view of a nature scene/wide area of beautiful land). Dalrymple (1986a, b) 
 reports that the total area of modern wheat and rice varieties under (producing crops/helping something grow) in sub-Saharan Africa in 1983 was about 800 000 ha (wheat 556 000 and 
 rice 242 000 ha) which is roughly equal to one-quarter of the once-a-year cropped area in Zimbabwe, one of the 45 countries in Mrica. Since the Green 
 Revolution has barely touched Africa, African leaders and the donor community must face up to the reality that the CGIAR and French research networks 
 have not delivered the volume of new food crop technology that many experts 
 had completely/in a hinting way promised when the first CGIAR center IITA, was established in 
 Ibadan some 20 years ago. Three lessons flow from the limited hit/effect of Green 
 Revolution in Africa to date. The first is the need to strengthen the ability (to hold or do something) 
 ofNARS to develop new technology and add to/addition the efforts of the CGIAR, 
 CIRAD and the worldwide  research system. The second is to strengthen the ability (to hold or do something) ofNARS to become (producing more with less waste) borrowers of technology from close-by 
 countries and the worldwide  research system. The third is the need for the CGIAR 
 to (look at again) its plan of strengthening the ability (to hold or do something) of the NARS of Africa. 
 Money from other countries buildup for NARS. In the 1960s and 1970s, (people who give money or other things) invested 
 heavily in developing the CGIAR worldwide  system, including four IARCs with 
 their headquarters based in Africa. In 1980, the CG system launched a new 
 institute, ISNAR, to help strengthen national farming-based research systems. 
 During the 1980s, (people who give money or other things) channeled investments to the NARS of Mrica. The 
 World Bank took the lead in co-financing a large loan for the NARS of Sudan 
 in 1979 followed by loans to Senegal, Rwanda, Malawi and other countries in 
 the early 1980s. The loans by the Bank and other (people who give money or other things) to African NARS in 
 the 1980s are noted for their conservative time frame (usually 5-7 years), 
