 Scientific ability (to hold or do something) building: 1990-2020 
 Drawing on Africa's research experience over the past 60 years, the following issues come out  for debate on strengthening national and (related to a large area) 
 farming-based research systems over the next 30 years: 
 
 Politics of science and technology for farming-based development. The central question to be talked to/looked at by African states, scientists and the international 
 community in the 1990s is the following: How can African nations of different 
 sizes organize themselves to become more (related to computers and science) skilled? The present donor-financed project by project and country by country approach to 
 building African scientific ability (to hold or do something) is seriously flawed. The road ahead needs/demands a vision of the changing role of science and technology in Mrica's (away from cities) 
 change over the next 25-50 years. There is an important need for the 
 NARS, the Special Program for African Farming-based Research (SPAAR) and 
 the major (people who give money or other things) to develop a long term (related to how land, rivers, etc. affect a country's rules and relationships) and coordinated approach 
 to scientific ability (to hold or do something)-building in Africa. But the foundation for this new vision 
 of the role of science and technology in Africa development must come from 
 Africa and must flow from Africa's historical, cultural, technical, and political 
 experience. For example, Professor Thomas Odhiambo of Kenya argues that 
 African "farming-based research leadership, in concert with the (related to how land, rivers, etc. affect a country's rules and relationships) 
 leadership, must create and care for an (surrounding conditions) that encourages research 
 business-starting and excites inventions" (Odhiambo, 1988, 
 p. 48). African scientific ability (to hold or do something)-building should also include long-term international money-based help for (related to a large area) research and MSc training institutions 
 (because of the small country problem) for at least the next 20-30 years. 
 Payoff to coordinated investments in research, extension and training. Most 
 studies reporting high rates of returns to investment in farming-based research 
 in Asia and Latin America and industrial countries are, in fact, combined returns 
 to investments in research, extension and training. The payoff to a coordinated 
 set of investments to strengthen the institutional base (research, extension, 
 and training) for farming is (taken by force/controlled) in a new study of U.S. 
 farming-based research by Evenson, Waggoner and Ruttan (1979). The authors 
 found that the highest payoffs to research came from a coordinated set of interactive investments to further the decentralization of research and the promotion of research-extension linkages. The end/end result that flows from this 
 study is the need to shift the debate from strengthening research to the coordination of investments in research, extension and training (Bonnen, 1987). 
 The issue for (people who give money or other things) to think about in the 1990s is the following: what national and 
 (related to a large area) (machines/methods/ways) need to be developed to strengthen the coordination of 
 research, extension and training institutions in support of African 
 farming? 
 
