 Farming-based research investment normal behaviors and (things that are important). How much should 
 African states spend on farming-based research? Now, most (people who give money or other things) follow 
 the guideline that a desirable farming-based research investment target would 
 be in the range of 0.5-2.0% of the total national value of farming-based GDP. 
 The World Bank has argued that a desirable investment target for research 
 for many countries would be a once-a-year expense (repeating, plus capital) 
 "equal to about 2 percent of farming-based gross domestic product" (World 
 Bank, 1981, p. 8). But this norm is taken from industrial countries with a 
 century or more of experience in (getting ready for action) political and money-based help 
 from farm organizations, valuable thing groups, private firms and state and 
 federal organizations. There is little scientific information from Africa on the 
 pay off to investing 0.5-2.0% of farming-based GDP in research. There is, 
 however, enough historical and (less than definite) evidence to decide that some of 
 the recent statements on the level of investment in NARS should be 
 taken with some doubt. For example, Dayanatha Jha (not very long ago) ended/decided 
 that there is "big underinvestment" in farming-based research in Africa 
 because 14 countries were spending less than 0.5% of their farming-based GDP 
 on research (Jha, 1987, p. 267). But the ready availability of money from other countries in the 
 1980s has led to an overinvestment in some NARS relative to their current 
 stage of institutional maturity, (able to/ability to hold or take in something else) ability (to hold or do something), scientific leadership, projected government money/money income, and political support to maintain the NARS after 
 money from other countries is phased out. For example, it is usually easier for the manager of a NARS to (get ready for action) an added million dollars of research 
 support from (people who give money or other things) than from domestic sources. Although Vernon Ruttan 
 (1987) has over and over again stressed the need to tie (in small steps up) donor money available for 
 NARS to matching money from the receiver government, in practice, (people who give money or other things) 
 are unwilling to enforce this common sense approach. 
 The farming-based research investment normal behaviors came/coming from the experience of 
