 Size, (things that are important) and performance of NARS. The size of many NARS has increased very much since independence in 1960. Four factors help explain the 
 growth of NARS and why this growth has often been at the expense of the 
 quality of the research program. First, since independence, as part of the (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of the state slow-working department, many NARS have increased the 
 number of scientists, technicians, buildings, equipment, research stations, 
 research projects, and operating budgets beyond the ability to sustain these activities from national budgets. In many cases, this (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) has outstripped 
 the ability (to hold or do something) oflocal research managers to restrict the number of research 
 problems talked to/looked at, manage the national research business/project, pay staff on 
 time, plant experiments on schedule, and (get ready for action) political and slow-working 
 support from the Ministry of Finance to finance and sustain the system after 
 money from other countries is phased out. For example, Nigeria's petroleum boom has fueled 
 the (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of its NARS from around 100 scientists at independence in 1960 
 to 1000 in 1989, but the research system is starved for operating money. Professor Francis Idachaba, Vice Chancellor of the University of Farming, 
 Makurdi (not very long ago) reported that "Research management probably makes up/is equal to 
 the most important restriction on Nigeria's National Farming-based Research 
 System" (Idachaba, 1987, p. 351). 
 Second, many NARS have been under lots of nagging to soak up 
 new university graduates. In Kenya, for example the NARs has been under 
 pressure to go beyond the (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) practice of hiring farming-based graduates to 
 accepting some of the growing number of science graduates from the 
 university system, a system that has grown from one university in 1970 to five 
 in 1989. 
 Third, (people who give money or other things) have directly and indirectly added/gave to the increase in the 
 size of NARS. For example, (people who give money or other things) are now paying a big share 
 of the repeating budget of the national farming-based research systems in Mali, 
 Ghana, Senegal, Niger, Zambia, Rwanda, and many other countries. It is 
 almost impossible to refer to  a donor (investigation to see if something can be done) that recommends reducing 
